307122359464341666940824949212165229736.text:
Let $S$ be a set.
Let $\RR$ be a transitive relation on $S$.
Let $\RR^=$ be the reflexive closure of $\RR$.
Let $a, b, c \in S$.
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | n = 1
      | l = \paren {a \mathrel \RR b} \land \paren {b \mathrel \RR c}
      | o = \implies
      | r = a \mathrel \RR c
}}
{{eqn | n = 2
      | l = \paren {a \mathrel \RR b} \land \paren {b \mathrel {\RR^=} c}
      | o = \implies
      | r = a \mathrel \RR c
}}
{{eqn | n = 3
      | l = \paren {a \mathrel {\RR^=} b} \land \paren {b \mathrel \RR c}
      | o = \implies
      | r = a \mathrel \RR c
}}
{{eqn | n = 4
      | l = \paren {a \mathrel {\RR^=} b} \land \paren {b \mathrel {\RR^=} c}
      | o = \implies
      | r = a \mathrel {\RR^=} c
}}
{{end-eqn}}
